      a: 1,
      x: "Equal concentrations and 1:1 stoichiometry, so V(NaOH) = C_a V_a / C_b = (0.100*25.0)/0.100 = 25.0 mL. The indicator does not change the equivalence volume."
    },
    {
      q: "At the equivalence point of a strong acid - strong base titration at 25 C, the pH is:",
      opts: ["Below 7", "Exactly 7", "Above 7", "Cannot be determined"],
      a: 1,
      x: "The salt formed (e.g. NaCl) is from a strong acid and strong base, so neither ion hydrolyses. The solution is neutral: pH = 7.00."
    },
    {
      q: "For a weak acid titrated with a strong base, what is true at the half-equivalence point?",
      opts: ["pH = 7", "pH = pKa", "pH = pKb", "The buffer capacity is at a minimum"],
      a: 1,
      x: "At half-equivalence [HA] = [A-], so the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation gives pH = pKa + log(1) = pKa. Buffer capacity is actually maximal here."
    },
    {
